export const EXTRA_PAIR_INSIGHTS: Record<string, Record<string, string>> = {
  'Mercury/Sun': {
    conjunction: 'Your thoughts and your identity are the same thing, which is why criticism of your ideas feels like a knife to the chest. You cannot present an opinion casually — every sentence you speak carries your whole self inside it. People experience you as articulate and certain, but the private cost is that you rarely get distance from your own mind. Changing your opinion feels like changing who you are, so you defend positions long after you have privately outgrown them. Learning to say \'I was wrong\' without feeling erased is the work of a lifetime.',
    opposition: 'You argue with yourself constantly — the voice in your head sounds like an opponent, not an ally. You seek out people who will debate you, challenge you, correct you, and then you resent them for it, because what you are really doing is outsourcing an internal war. You articulate other people\'s positions brilliantly and your own poorly. The turning point comes when you stop needing a sparring partner to know what you think, and let your mind serve your identity instead of cross-examining it.',
    trine: 'Words come to you the way breathing comes to everyone else. You explain yourself easily, you are believed easily, and you have probably never experienced the agony of being chronically misunderstood. That is the trap. Because expression costs you nothing, you rarely dig for the thought underneath the fluent one — you deliver the first clever sentence instead of the true one. People call you a natural communicator. You will become a great one only when you start saying the things that are hard for you to say.',
    square: 'What you mean and what comes out of your mouth are two different people. You interrupt yourself, over-explain, or say the sharp thing and spend the drive home rewriting it. Your mind moves at an angle to your sense of self, so you often sound more arrogant, more uncertain, or more combative than you actually feel. The friction is the gift: because self-expression never came free, you have been forced to actually examine what you believe. Your hardest-won sentences are worth more than other people\'s easy ones.',
    sextile: 'Your mind and your identity cooperate — when you decide to speak up, you are heard, and when you decide to think something through, you get somewhere. But notice the word \'decide\'. Nothing here is automatic. You have watched opportunities pass because you assumed someone else would say the thing you were thinking. The talent is real: you can translate who you are into words that land. It simply waits for you to volunteer. Every time you speak first in a room, your life gets measurably better.',
    quincunx: 'Your mind never quite speaks your language. You know exactly who you are until someone asks you to explain it, and then the words come out beside the point — too technical, too flippant, too much about something else. You have learned to manage this with humor or silence, but the mismatch is permanent, and the adjustment is the skill: you will always need to translate yourself deliberately, checking that what landed matches what you meant. People who take that extra sentence from you are getting the real thing.',
  },
  'Mars/Sun': {
    conjunction: 'Your will and your identity are welded together — wanting something and being someone are the same act for you. You move first and understand your reasons later, and you experience obstacles as personal insults rather than neutral facts. People read you as brave, decisive, sometimes exhausting. What they do not see is that you literally cannot tell the difference between losing a fight and losing yourself, which is why you keep fighting past the point of sense. Your life improves the day you learn to lose small battles on purpose.',
    opposition: 'You project your aggression onto other people and then wonder why your life is full of combative bosses, pushy partners, and drivers who cut you off. The anger is yours — you have just made everyone else carry it. You are magnetic in conflict, oddly calm when others explode, because their fire is familiar; it is your own, reflected. The pattern breaks when you start wanting things openly and fighting for them directly, instead of waiting for an opponent to give you permission to push back.',
    trine: 'Action comes easily to you — you decide, you move, doors open, and you have quietly concluded that people who struggle simply are not trying. That is the blind spot of this gift. Your energy and your identity flow in the same direction, so you have never had to fight yourself to get out of bed, start the project, or make the call. The risk is coasting on momentum instead of aiming it: you win the races you happen to enter. Choose harder races. Ease without ambition becomes a pleasant, forgettable life.',
    square: 'Your drive fights your identity like a horse fighting its rider. You want things fiercely and then sabotage the wanting — starting fights on the eve of success, quitting jobs the month before the promotion, burning energy proving yourself to people you do not respect. Anger arrives before understanding, and you have hurt people in the gap. But this friction builds real strength: every time you harness the horse instead of shooting it, you become someone forceful AND deliberate. The people who master this aspect become unstoppable. Most never do. You could.',
    sextile: 'Your courage is available on request — that is the precise truth of this aspect. You are not compulsively driven, but when you commit to something, your energy shows up fully and your identity backs it without conflict. The catch is that you must place the order. Left idle, this aspect produces a capable person who watches less talented, more aggressive people pass them. You have seen it happen and it stung. The sting was correct. Initiative is the entire price of everything this aspect is offering you.',
    quincunx: 'Your energy never arrives when your identity needs it. You are exhausted before the interview and wired at midnight; passive when you should push and forceful over things that do not matter. You have privately wondered if something is wrong with your wiring. Nothing is wrong — your drive and your selfhood simply run on different clocks, permanently. The adjustment is logistical, not moral: schedule your battles for when the energy is actually there, and stop judging yourself by people whose fire and identity happen to be synchronized.',
  },
  'Mercury/Moon': {
    conjunction: 'You cannot think without feeling or feel without narrating. Every emotion arrives pre-verbalized, running as commentary in your head, and every thought carries an emotional charge you cannot strip out. This makes you a natural confidant — people sense that you will actually understand — but it also means you have never once had an objective opinion about anything that matters to you. Your memories are moods. Your arguments are feelings wearing logic. Honor that instead of hiding it: your subjective truth, spoken plainly, is more persuasive than your borrowed objectivity.',
    opposition: 'Your head and your heart take turns running your life, and they do not brief each other. You make the rational choice and feel homesick for the one you rejected; you follow the feeling and your mind files a formal protest for years. In conversation you swing between clinical detachment and sudden emotional flooding, and the people close to you never know which one is coming. You keep looking for someone who will be the heart to your head or vice versa. Stop outsourcing. The negotiation is internal, and it never adjourns.',
    trine: 'You say how you feel with an ease that other people find almost unfair. Emotions move through you into words without friction, which makes you soothing to be around — the friend who names the thing everyone else was circling. The danger is fluency without depth: because feelings translate so smoothly, you can narrate your inner life instead of actually living it, describing sadness beautifully rather than sitting in it. Your words heal people. Make sure they occasionally cost you something, or you will become eloquent and untouched.',
    square: 'Your feelings and your words are permanently out of tune. You go quiet exactly when you need to speak, and speak sharply exactly when you need to be soft. After emotional conversations you replay them for days, composing the sentence you should have said. People have called you cold when you were overwhelmed and dramatic when you were precise. This friction is forging something rare: because expression never came cheap, when you finally do say the true thing, it lands with a weight that fluent people never achieve.',
    sextile: 'When you choose to open up, it goes well — people receive you warmly, the words come, the feeling clarifies as you speak it. Notice that every good conversation in your life started because someone decided to have it, and it usually was not you. Your heart and mind cooperate beautifully but neither one volunteers. You will wait weeks holding a feeling that would have dissolved in one honest sentence. The aspect asks almost nothing of you: start the conversation. That is the whole toll, every time.',
    quincunx: 'What you feel and what you can say about it never quite match, and they never will. You describe anger and realize later it was grief; you write the perfect message and feel worse after sending it. Others seem to have a direct line between heart and mouth that you were not issued. Stop waiting for it. Your adjustment is the workaround: feel first, speak later, revise often. The gap that frustrates you is also why your eventual words are considered, layered, and strangely precise — you have to translate, so you actually look.',
  },
  'Moon/Venus': {
    conjunction: 'Being loved and being safe are the same thing in your body — you cannot tell them apart, and you have never tried. You soothe yourself with beauty, food, affection, comfort, and you make the people around you feel exquisitely cared for, because caring is how you breathe. The shadow is that you will keep the peace at almost any price. You swallow objections, sweeten conflicts, and call it love. Some of it is. Some of it is fear wearing love\'s clothes, and only you can tell which is which.',
    opposition: 'What you need and what you want in love are two different people, and you keep dating both of them. You choose partners who feel like home and get bored, or partners who thrill you and never feel safe. Then you make the other person responsible for the half you exiled — demanding excitement from the stable one, security from the wild one. The tug-of-war ends when you admit both hungers are yours. No one person failed you. You split the assignment and graded them each on the half they never got.',
    trine: 'Affection comes easily to you and always has — you were probably loved well, or learned early how to be lovable, and warmth now follows you into rooms. People relax around you without knowing why. Here is what you do not see: because comfort arrives on its own, you have never had to fight for a relationship, and so you quietly withdraw from any love that requires fighting. You mistake ease for compatibility and friction for failure. The best things you will ever have are on the far side of an argument you keep avoiding.',
    square: 'Your need for comfort and your need for love keep sabotaging each other. You get cozy and stop courting; you fall in love and lose your appetite, your sleep, your routines. Pleasure carries a faint guilt for you — somewhere you absorbed the idea that you can be taken care of or desired, not both. So you overgive, then binge on private comfort, then resent the people you overgave to. The growth is learning that your needs are not negotiations. Say the want out loud, unsweetened, and watch who stays.',
    sextile: 'You have a real talent for warmth — for making moments soft, for reading what someone needs and providing it almost invisibly. But this aspect only pays out when you act on it. Left passive, it becomes pleasant loneliness: you are lovely to everyone and intimate with no one, waiting to be chosen because choosing feels forward. Every close relationship you treasure exists because somebody initiated. Take a turn. The invitation you keep not extending — the dinner, the apology, the confession — is the door this aspect has been holding open for years.',
    quincunx: 'What comforts you and what you find beautiful refuse to line up. You crave closeness, then feel crowded the moment you get it; you want to be adored, then flinch at the adoration because it arrives in the wrong dialect. Partners say you are hard to please and they are not wrong — the target moves. It will always move. The adjustment is naming your needs in real time instead of expecting anyone to intuit a pattern even you cannot predict. The lovers who last with you are the ones you kept updated.',
  },
  'Mercury/Uranus': {
    conjunction: 'Your mind does not walk from A to B — it teleports, and you have spent your whole life waiting for other people to catch up. Insights arrive whole, sideways, at strange hours, and you say them out loud before checking whether the room is ready. You are the person who blurts the true thing at the wrong moment. School likely bored you into misbehavior. The gift is genuine original thought; the tax is impatience with every mind slower than yours, which is most of them. Learn to build bridges back to your conclusions.',
    opposition: 'You experience your own genius as coming from other people. You are drawn to brilliant, erratic, disruptive minds — friends who blow up your worldview, mentors who electrify then abandon you — and around them you play the reasonable one. But the lightning is yours; you have just assigned it to whoever seems safer holding it. You argue against radical ideas in public and rehearse them alone at 2am. The shift comes when you say your own strange thought under your own name and let someone else be the audience.',
    trine: 'Original ideas come to you so naturally that you assume everyone has them and simply chooses not to mention it. Your mind refreshes itself: you get unstuck while others are still describing the stuckness, and new technology, new frameworks, new slang cost you nothing to absorb. The risk is that brilliance without pressure never compounds. You have a drawer full of insights you never built, because the next one always arrived before the last one demanded anything. Pick one idea and stay with it past the point of boredom. That is where genius becomes work.',
    square: 'Your best ideas arrive as interruptions — derailing your plans, your sentences, your carefully built positions. You contradict yourself mid-argument because a truer thought just landed, and people call you erratic when actually you are updating faster than you can announce. You have quit things abruptly and been right, and quit things abruptly and been wrong, and cannot always tell which is coming. This friction is training you to hold voltage without dropping it. The thinkers who change fields have exactly this wiring — plus the discipline you are still building.',
    sextile: 'You can innovate on demand — when you sit down to find the unconventional angle, it is reliably there. That reliability has made you lazy about it. You save your originality for emergencies and run on autopilot the rest of the time, nodding along in meetings while privately seeing the better way. Nobody knows how differently you think, because divergence, for you, requires a decision and you ration your decisions. Stop rationing. Every time you have voiced the weird idea, it aged well. Your track record is begging you to trust it.',
    quincunx: 'Your flashes of insight never arrive on topic. You get the answer to last month\'s problem during this month\'s crisis; you are brilliant in the shower and ordinary in the meeting. It feels like owning a genius who keeps missing appointments. This never fully resolves — the timing is structurally off. The adjustment is capture: write the flashes down when they come, because they are solving real problems, just asynchronously. People with tidy minds produce tidy work. Your untidy channel, properly archived, produces the thing nobody else could have thought of.',
  },
  'Mercury/Neptune': {
    conjunction: 'The membrane between your thoughts and your imagination never fully formed. You remember conversations that happened slightly differently, believe things because they are beautiful, and can convince yourself of nearly anything — which makes you a natural poet and an unreliable witness, including to yourself. People are enchanted by how you talk and occasionally lied to by it, without malice, because you were inside the dream while telling it. Your words can heal, sell, and mesmerize. Keep one ruthless friend who checks your facts, and never make them wrong for it.',
    opposition: 'You are drawn to people who confuse you. Vague communicators, beautiful evaders, partners whose stories never quite add up — and you, ordinarily sharp, go soft-focus around them, explaining away contradictions you would flag instantly in anyone else. The fog is yours; you have projected your own longing to be deceived onto people willing to oblige. You alternate between cynicism and gullibility, calling both of them clarity. The pattern breaks when you admit you sometimes prefer the beautiful story to the true one, and start choosing consciously which one you are buying.',
    trine: 'Imagination and intellect flow together in you without effort — you explain abstract things with images, you sense what people mean underneath what they say, and your intuition about unspoken currents in a room is quietly excellent. The danger is that this gift works unattended, so you never train it. You settle for being the person with good vibes and lovely metaphors instead of the one who writes the book, scores the film, names the thing. Sensitivity this fluent is a professional instrument. Coasting on it as a personality trait is the waste of a life.',
    square: 'Your clarity keeps dissolving right when you reach for it. You explain something perfectly in your head and hear it come out fogged; you sign things you half-read, trust summaries that were wrong, lose arguments you were winning to a sudden blankness. You have been called scattered, spacey, even dishonest, when the truth is your mind and your imagination are wrestling over the same steering wheel. The forging is real: because you cannot trust easy clarity, you have to verify, draft, and revise — and your finished thinking outclasses everyone who got it right the first time.',
    sextile: 'You can translate between the practical and the ineffable — explain the vision to the accountants and the spreadsheet to the dreamers — but only when you make the effort, and you frequently do not. The intuition is accurate; you simply fail to act on it, then watch events confirm the hunch you kept to yourself. Count how many times you have said \'I knew that was going to happen\'. That phrase is this aspect, unclaimed. Start saying the hunch out loud before events confirm it. Your credibility will survive the misses. It will not survive the silence.',
    quincunx: 'Your intuition and your intellect refuse to testify at the same hearing. You sense something is wrong but cannot construct the argument, so you dismiss the feeling — and it turns out to have been right, in a way logic only reconstructs afterward. Or you build the airtight case and a wordless unease vetoes it. This mismatch is permanent. Stop demanding your knowing arrive in essay form. The adjustment is running two systems and letting each one file its report separately: act when they agree, and go slowly — very slowly — when they do not.',
  },
  'Uranus/Venus': {
    conjunction: 'You love like lightning — suddenly, totally, and with an exit door always in your peripheral vision. The moment a relationship becomes predictable, something in you starts pacing. You have ended good things because they were only good, and you attract unusual people because ordinary affection feels like a costume. What no one sees: your detachment is not coldness, it is terror of losing yourself inside another person. The partner who lasts will be the one who never fully closes the door — leaving you free enough that you finally stop needing to leave.',
    opposition: 'Chaos in love always seems to be the other person\'s fault. You choose stable partners and then meet someone electric; you choose electric partners and they detonate the life you built. Every relationship becomes a referendum between security and freedom, with the other person cast as whichever side you disowned. But look at the pattern — you are the constant. The disruption is your own hunger for aliveness, hired out to whoever is willing to play the wild card. Own the hunger, and you can finally stay without feeling buried alive.',
    trine: 'Freedom and love coexist in you without argument — you give partners room to breathe and genuinely do not spiral when they take it. Your relationships are refreshingly free of possessiveness, and unconventional arrangements that would break other couples simply work for you. Here is the coasting risk: your ease with space can become a way of never landing. You are so comfortable with loose ties that you drift out of loves worth fighting for, blessing everyone\'s freedom including your own exit. Sometimes the radical move, for you, is staying when you do not have to.',
    square: 'Your heart wants closeness and your nervous system treats closeness as captivity, and they take turns winning. You pull people in with real warmth, then go cold without warning — cancel plans, need space, pick a fight that manufactures distance — and then miss them the moment they retreat. Partners describe you as hot and cold; you experience it as suffocation and loneliness alternating. The friction is forging a person who can be deeply attached without being owned. Until then, tell people the truth mid-episode: \'This is mine, not yours. Do not go far.\'',
    sextile: 'You have easy access to a rare skill — refreshing love before it goes stale. You can reinvent a relationship, propose the strange trip, renegotiate the arrangement, and it works when you do it. The problem is you mostly do not. You wait until the boredom has already curdled into resentment, then blame the relationship for a staleness you had the tools to disrupt months earlier. This aspect is opportunity, not weather. The unconventional gesture you keep postponing — make it while there is still something alive to electrify.',
    quincunx: 'What excites you and what you can hold onto are permanently mismatched. The thrilling ones exhaust you; the steady ones dim something in you; and each time you adjust toward one pole, the other starts aching. You have concluded, privately, that you might be unbuildable for — too weird for the normal ones, too normal for the weird ones. Wrong conclusion. The adjustment never ends, but it can be honest: pick the person you can keep recalibrating WITH, out loud, rather than the fantasy of a fit that requires no adjustment at all.',
  },
  'Jupiter/Mars': {
    conjunction: 'Your desires arrive supersized. When you want something, you want it enormously, immediately, and with total confidence that the universe will underwrite the check. Often it does — your boldness opens doors that careful people never even knock on. But you chronically overcommit: three projects, two feuds, one grand plan, all at full throttle, because moderation feels like a kind of death. People are swept up by you and occasionally flattened. The lesson you keep tuition-paying for: enthusiasm is not a strategy, and not every green light is a sign.',
    opposition: 'You oscillate between crusade and collapse. You commit your energy to something huge, evangelize it, overextend — then the faith drains out overnight and you cannot remember why it mattered. Meanwhile you attract grandiose people, big talkers whose confidence you first fund and later resent, because their excess is your own, projected and outsourced. The tug-of-war ends when you stop needing every effort to be a holy war. Medium-sized actions, taken daily, in the same direction — that is the discipline this aspect withholds until you choose it deliberately.',
    trine: 'Luck follows your effort so reliably that you have never learned the difference between the two. You act, things expand; you push, doors swing; and your default optimism has been ratified by results often enough to feel like law. Enjoy it — and notice the sedative inside it. Because winning came easy, you pick easy games. You are running at sixty percent and being applauded for it, which is exactly why you have never found your ceiling. Find a fight big enough to require all of you. You have not had one yet.',
    square: 'Your confidence writes checks your capacity has to scramble to cash. You promise big, start hot, and hit the wall where enthusiasm meets logistics — then rather than admit the miscalculation, you push harder, and the pushing is where your injuries, blowups, and burned bridges come from. You have a gambler\'s relationship with your own energy. But this friction, survived, forges the rarest kind of achiever: one whose boldness has scar tissue. Every humbling has made your aim better. The size of your reach was never the problem. The refusal to measure was.',
    sextile: 'Opportunity and energy cooperate in you — when you pursue something, momentum genuinely builds, allies appear, the path widens. Your history proves it: everything you have chased with real commitment has grown. The problem is how rarely you choose to chase. You are a strong starter who mostly does not start, living in the gap between what you could do and what you feel like doing today. This aspect will not push you; it only matches your bets. Small bet, small growth. You have been making small bets for years. Raise.',
    quincunx: 'Your energy and your optimism are never full at the same time. When you believe in the plan you cannot summon the push; when the push finally comes, the faith has quietly left the building. You start things at the wrong size — too grand when you are dreaming, too timid when you are doing — and the calibration never becomes automatic. That is the permanent adjustment: audit your commitments against your actual fuel, in writing, because your instincts will always misreport one or the other. Managed honestly, this mismatch becomes range. Ignored, it becomes a résumé of almosts.',
  },
  'Mars/Uranus': {
    conjunction: 'Your body runs on voltage, not fuel. You act in bursts — sudden, total, unannounced — and the people who love you have learned to brace when you go quiet, because quiet means the next lightning strike is loading. Routine physically hurts you; you would rather blow up a stable situation than serve out its sentence. You are genuinely fearless in moments that terrify others, and genuinely reckless in moments that require patience. Accidents, walkouts, electric decisions: your history is punctuated, not flowing. Your freedom is real. Aim it, or it will keep aiming you.',
    opposition: 'Explosions happen near you, and you are always somehow standing innocently at the center. Volatile colleagues, partners who snap, strangers who pick you out of a crowd to confront — your life is full of other people\'s sudden aggression, which should tell you something. The disruption is yours; you have just perfected the art of provoking it without fingerprints. That maddening calm you keep during other people\'s outbursts is the poker face of a disowned rebel. Claim your own defiance openly and watch how quickly the ambushes stop finding you.',
    trine: 'Your instincts are fast and your nerve is genuine — in a crisis you act while others are still gasping, and your improvised moves work with suspicious frequency. Risk simply costs you less than it costs other people. The trap is that gifts without resistance stay recreational. You spend this brilliance on hobbies, on driving fast, on being the spontaneous friend, because nothing has ever forced you to weaponize it toward something that matters. Reflexes like yours are wasted on low stakes. Volunteer for the emergency. You are built for exactly what everyone else avoids.',
    square: 'Your anger has a hair trigger and terrible timing. The pressure builds invisibly — you do not even feel it — and then some minor thing detonates a response sized for every slight you have swallowed for months. You have quit, sworn, sent it, said it, and stood in the wreckage thinking that was not the plan. There was no plan; that is the point. This friction is forging the hardest discipline there is: keeping your nerve AND your judgment in the same moment. Insert one breath between impulse and action. One. Everything you have ever regretted lived inside that missing breath.',
    sextile: 'You have a talent for the decisive unconventional move — the sidestep nobody considered, the abrupt pivot that turns out to be the whole game. When you use it, it works. You just barely ever use it, because your daily life is arranged to require nothing sudden of you. So the voltage leaks out sideways: restlessness, impatience in traffic, fantasies of quitting dramatically. That energy is not a mood, it is unspent capital. Pick one stuck situation this month and make the abrupt move you keep rehearsing. Your rehearsals are consistently better than your excuses.',
    quincunx: 'Your impulses fire at structurally wrong moments — bold when the situation needs stillness, frozen when it begs for speed. You have watched slower people act at the right time and win, while your superior reflexes sat in the wrong queue. It reads as bad luck. It is bad synchronization, and it is permanent, so build for it: decide your triggers in advance — if X happens, I do Y — because your in-the-moment timing will never be trustworthy. Pre-decided, your daring is a precision tool. Improvised, it is a firework in a filing cabinet.',
  },
  'Mars/Neptune': {
    conjunction: 'Your drive is mixed with fog at the source. You pursue dreams with real energy and real energy with dreaminess — charging hard at goals that dissolve on approach, or drifting past targets you could have hit in your sleep. Your anger is the same: it rarely comes out straight, surfacing instead as withdrawal, martyrdom, or a mysterious exhaustion that is rage wearing a nightgown. At your best you act on inspiration others cannot even see, like an artist or a mystic with a sword. At your worst you cannot tell crusade from mirage. Check which one you are holding. Regularly.',
    opposition: 'You keep meeting people who drain your will. Colleagues whose problems become your workload, partners whose dreams you fund with your energy while yours sit parked, charismatic causes that consume years and evaporate. You call it generosity. Look closer: you are outsourcing your own longing for surrender, letting others dissolve the willpower you are ambivalent about owning. The resentment you feel afterward is the receipt. The pattern ends when you give your effort to your own dream first — on purpose, on schedule — and make everyone else\'s emergency wait its turn.',
    trine: 'Your actions carry an unforced grace — you pursue things without visible strain, and people describe you as effortless, intuitive, easy to root for. You can act on a hunch and land it, work toward invisible goals without needing proof, inspire effort in others without raising your voice. The coasting risk is severe: because pushing was never required, you may have never once pushed. Your dreams stay pleasant precisely because they stay theoretical. Effortlessness that never meets resistance is indistinguishable from sleep. Pick a dream and put your back into it — grace under load is your actual gift.',
    square: 'Your will and your dreams keep fouling each other\'s lines. You work hard in the wrong direction, or know the right direction and cannot summon the wattage; you commit to plans and a strange lethargy dissolves them from the inside. You have been accused of laziness by people who never saw how hard you were rowing under the fog. The forging is this: you are being forced to make your motivation conscious. Others run on automatic desire; yours must be hand-built, examined, renewed. That constructed will, once built, is immune to disillusionment in a way theirs will never be.',
    sextile: 'You can put muscle behind a vision — organize the benefit, ship the creative project, turn compassion into logistics — and when you do, it lands with unusual beauty. That conversion skill is rare, and you treat it like a hobby setting. Your imagination produces constantly; your follow-through samples occasionally. Meanwhile you feel a low-grade melancholy you cannot name, which is what unexpressed vision does to a nervous system. This aspect asks for initiative, not talent — the talent is already installed. One dream, moved deliberately into the world per year, would change your entire relationship with yourself.',
    quincunx: 'Your effort and your inspiration live in different time zones and never fully sync. When you are inspired the energy is missing; when the energy arrives the vision has gone abstract, and pushing harder only thickens the fog. You have cycled between overwork and mysterious depletion and called yourself inconsistent. You are not inconsistent — you are running an engine and a tide on one dashboard, forever. The adjustment: act small during fog, dream freely during fatigue, and never make major moves when either gauge is spiking. Mid-range is where all your best work will happen.',
  },
  'Jupiter/Uranus': {
    conjunction: 'You are wired for the lucky break, and you know it — your life pivots on sudden windfalls, chance meetings, doors that open the moment you stop knocking. This has made you allergic to the gradual. You want the leap, not the ladder, and you will detonate a comfortable situation purely because it stopped surprising you. Your beliefs update in jolts; you have abandoned whole worldviews overnight and never looked back. The gift is genuine: freedom-seeking that actually finds freedom. The tax: everyone who tried to plan a future with you.',
    opposition: 'Other people\'s recklessness fascinates and infuriates you. You watch friends bet everything on wild ventures — some crash, some get rich — while you hold the sensible line and feel something like grief. Or you flip: you become the wild one and collect cautious partners who audit your every leap. Either way, half of you is always in someone else\'s custody. The freedom you envy and the prudence you resent are both yours. Take the risk YOU have vetted, rather than living through gamblers or being supervised by accountants.',
    trine: 'Change is kind to you, and it always has been. Upheavals that wreck other people somehow deposit you somewhere better — the layoff that led to the better job, the canceled plan that opened the real path. You trust the unexpected, and the unexpected rewards your trust. The coasting risk: because fortune improvises well on your behalf, you never learned to aim it. You surf whatever wave arrives instead of choosing a destination, mistaking pleasant turbulence for a direction. Luck this reliable deserves a target. Point it at something enormous, deliberately, once.',
    square: 'Your breakthroughs arrive at the worst possible times. The new opportunity lands mid-commitment; the revelation strikes right after you signed the lease; your faith in the plan collapses at the exact moment quitting costs the most. So your growth happens in lurches — overexpansion, correction, sudden swerve — and steadier people have learned to stand back. But this friction teaches what smooth luck never could: how to change direction under load, at speed, without losing the cargo. People who master this aspect do not avoid upheaval. They get good at it. You are getting good at it.',
    sextile: 'Opportunity knocks for you in odd disguises — the weird invitation, the tangent conversation, the job posting that does not quite fit — and when you have said yes to strangeness, it has consistently paid. Your history of best things traces back to your least sensible yeses. Yet your default is still the polite no; you honor the plan and decline the door. This aspect will keep sending doors, but it will not open them for you, and the knocking gets quieter every year you spend proving you are not home. Say yes to the next odd thing. It is load-bearing.',
    quincunx: 'Your luck and your liberation never arrive in the same package. The windfall comes with a cage attached; the freedom comes broke; the opportunity of a lifetime demands the one thing you just committed elsewhere. You have concluded that the universe has a bookkeeping error with your name on it. The mismatch is permanent, so master the trade: every expansion will cost some freedom, every liberation some security, and pretending otherwise is where all your bitterness comes from. Price the trade consciously, choose fast, and stop mourning the option you did not take. Both doors were real. You only ever get one.',
  },
  'Jupiter/Neptune': {
    conjunction: 'Your faith has no ceiling and no floor. You believe totally — in the vision, the teacher, the plan, the person — and your belief is so vivid it recruits other people\'s hope along with your own. Then the object of faith turns out to be human-sized, and the collapse is total too. You have been called naive by people who never built anything and inspired by people who built things because of you. Both are right. Keep the boundless faith; it is your engine. Just stop installing it in single points of failure.',
    opposition: 'You keep enthroning other people as the keeper of meaning — the guru, the visionary partner, the friend whose spiritual life seems realer than yours — and then dethroning them when their humanity shows. Each cycle leaves you more cynical, and your cynicism is just heartbroken faith wearing armor. The pattern is projection: the transcendence you keep finding in others is your own, handed over because owning it feels grandiose. It is not grandiose. Build your own practice, your own meaning, your own altar. Nobody else was ever supposed to hold that for you.',
    trine: 'Hope comes easily to you — a background trust that things will work out, which, disproportionately, they do. Kindness finds you, coincidences favor you, and your generosity circulates back on a delay you have stopped questioning. This grace is real, and it has made you spiritually flabby. You have never had to construct faith in a ruin, so your optimism remains untested weather rather than chosen conviction. When the real storm comes — it comes for everyone — vague trust will not hold. Deepen the well now, while it is easy. Ease is exactly when nobody does.',
    square: 'Your beliefs keep outrunning reality and getting yanked back. You inflate — the venture, the romance, the awakening — ride the vision past every warning sign, then crash into a disillusionment that feels like the death of meaning itself. Others learned to sip hope; you chug it and hit the floor. But watch what the cycle is forging: each collapse has burned off a layer of fantasy while leaving the faith itself intact, and that is the rarest outcome there is. Most people protect the fantasy and lose the faith. You are doing it in the right order. Keep going.',
    sextile: 'You have a working connection between belief and imagination — you can make hope contagious, tell the story that reorients a room, comfort people without lying to them. It activates the moment you engage it, and lies dormant the moment you do not, which is most of the time. You treat your own inner life like a vacation home: visited occasionally, loved abstractly, unlived-in. Meanwhile people around you are starving for exactly the meaning you can dispense. Volunteer it. Teach, write, console, bless — on purpose, on a schedule. Unshared, this gift quietly ferments into wistfulness.',
    quincunx: 'Your optimism and your imagination never agree on the size of things. You have grand faith in vague dreams and no faith in achievable ones; the practical opportunity feels spiritually empty while the impossible one feels like destiny. So you oscillate — inflated, then deflated, then inflated about deflation itself. This calibration error is permanent. The adjustment: submit every dream to one mundane test (what would I do about this on Tuesday?) and every practical plan to one meaning test (does any part of me love this?). Pursue only what survives both questions. Almost nothing will. That is the point.',
  },
  'Jupiter/Pluto': {
    conjunction: 'You do not want success — you want empire. There is a compulsion in your ambition that ordinary strivers do not have: winning must also transform, dominate, leave a crater. You attract resources, loyalty, and power with unsettling ease, and you attract the corruption tests that come with them. You have already felt it — the moment where you could push an advantage past what is fair, and something in you wanted to. Your becomes-legend potential and your becomes-cautionary-tale potential are the same trait. The only difference is what you do in that moment. There will be more of them.',
    opposition: 'Powerful people keep appearing across the table from you. Bosses who demand loyalty oaths, mentors whose help comes with hooks, institutions that grow you and then try to own you. You experience your life as a series of negotiations with someone stronger — but count the pattern: you keep choosing those tables. The hunger for scale is yours, projected onto whoever already has it. The tug-of-war ends when you stop apprenticing yourself to power and start openly wanting your own. You were never the small one in those rooms. You were the one in disguise.',
    trine: 'Influence accrues to you without visible effort — people hand you authority you did not request, ventures you touch tend to grow, and doors open on the strength of a presence you did not know you were projecting. It is easy to mistake this for being liked. It is not; it is power, arriving quietly, and unexamined power always finds a use for itself. The coasting risk here is moral: you can reshape rooms and lives half-asleep. Wake up. Decide what all this leverage is FOR, or one day you will discover what it decided on its own.',
    square: 'Every ambition of yours triggers a power struggle — with gatekeepers, with rivals, with institutions that seem personally offended by your growth. You push, something pushes back hard, and losing does not humble you, it deepens the vow. There is a ruthlessness available to you in these fights that occasionally frightens you when you glimpse it. Good — stay frightened of it; that is the leash. This friction is forging someone who can survive the acquisition of power, which is rarer than acquiring it. The struggles are not blocking your path. For you, they ARE the path.',
    sextile: 'You have a talent for regeneration at scale — walking into the failing project, the broken team, the dying idea, and finding the live nerve that revives it. When you have done this, it worked, and people remembered. But it only happens when you step forward, and your instinct is to wait for formal invitation. Power does not send invitations; it responds to occupancy. The room you are quietly auditing right now, the situation you could turn around — nobody is going to appoint you. Begin anyway. Your entire history says the authority arrives after you start, never before.',
    quincunx: 'Your growth and your power refuse to happen in the same place. Where you expand, you have no control; where you have control, everything stays small. The big break demands you abandon your base; the base rewards you for staying minor. You have split the difference for years and called it patience. It is not patience, it is a permanent structural tax, and the adjustment is to stop expecting one arena to give you both. Grow loudly in one, hold power quietly in another, and ferry resources between them. Empires with two capitals are still empires.',
  },
  'Saturn/Uranus': {
    conjunction: 'You are a revolution wearing a suit. Order and rebellion are fused in you: you build structures with real discipline, then feel imprisoned by exactly what you built. You are the rule-follower who suddenly quits, the rebel with an immaculate filing system, and both are the true you. People never know which one is coming, and honestly, neither do you — the switch flips without notice. Your rare gift is making radical things actually work, giving chaos a load-bearing frame. The lifelong labor is timing: knowing which situations need your architect and which need your arsonist.',
    opposition: 'Your life keeps splitting into wardens and anarchists. Rigid bosses versus flaky friends, the traditional parent versus the wild one, the stable career versus the escape fantasy — and you shuttle between camps, playing rebel to the rigid and grown-up to the reckless. You are exhausted from being everyone\'s counterweight. Both poles are yours: the hunger for structure and the hunger to smash it live in you, not in them. Stop calibrating yourself against other people\'s extremes. Build a life with strong walls and one permanently open door, and both hungers go quiet.',
    trine: 'You modernize without destroying — it is a genuinely uncommon gift. You can update the tradition, reform the system from inside, introduce the new method without triggering the antibodies, and old institutions trust you with changes they would refuse from anyone else. The coasting risk: incrementalism can become your hiding place. Because you CAN change things smoothly, you never test whether some things deserve to be broken outright. There is at least one structure in your life right now that needs demolition, not renovation, and your talent for gradual reform is the excuse it hides behind.',
    square: 'You build and burn in cycles. Years of discipline, then a rupture — the sudden resignation, the exploded routine, the relationship torched at its most stable — followed by guilt, followed by rebuilding, followed by the next rupture. You have privately wondered if you are self-sabotaging. Mostly, no: your need for freedom genuinely conflicts with your need for security, and each accrues debt while the other governs. The forging is learning to pay both continuously — scheduled rebellion inside committed structure — instead of alternating regimes. People who master this square change the world\'s actual institutions. It is that same voltage.',
    sextile: 'You can institutionalize your innovations — take the clever workaround and make it the official process, turn the experiment into the standard. When you bother, it works, and some things you casually systematized years ago are probably still running without you. But you underrate this constantly, treating your improvements as too obvious to formalize. They are not obvious; that is why nobody else built them. The initiative this aspect demands is documentation and follow-through: write the method down, name it, propose it upward. You keep waiting for the system to notice your genius. Systems notice paperwork.',
    quincunx: 'Your discipline and your originality refuse to shake hands. When you are structured, your inventiveness flatlines; when inspiration hits, your systems collapse and the bills go unpaid. Every productivity method you have adopted has strangled the exact spark it was supposed to serve, and every free period has dissolved into formless drift. This never fully fixes. The adjustment is segregation: rigid containers around small hours of total freedom — the same two hours, protected like a law, inside which no rules apply. You cannot blend these two natures. But you can absolutely schedule their custody arrangement.',
  },
  'Neptune/Saturn': {
    conjunction: 'Your dreams and your duties are welded together, which means you cannot fantasize without immediately auditing the fantasy. Every vision arrives with its own bill attached; every responsibility carries a faint dream inside it. At your best, this makes you the rare person who actually ships the impossible thing — the practical mystic, the artist with deadlines. At your worst, doubt dissolves your discipline while duty dissolves your dreams, and you end up grinding joylessly toward goals you no longer believe in. Check yearly: is the structure serving the dream, or has it quietly replaced it?',
    opposition: 'You keep casting other people as either the dreamer or the adult, and playing the opposite. With flaky idealists you become rigid and resentful; with rigid realists you become vague and slippery. The marriage of your inner mystic and your inner manager keeps being staged externally, as conflict, with real people playing the halves you disowned. Notice how you argue for practicality in one relationship and possibility in another, on the same day. Both voices are yours. Convene them privately, and the exhausting cast of opposites in your life will finally be allowed to be whole people.',
    trine: 'You give dreams skeletons without killing them — quietly turning inspiration into routine, vision into craft, faith into competence. People experience you as grounded AND deep, which is rare enough that they remember it. The coasting hazard: your peace between the practical and the spiritual came free, so you may have settled into a modest version of both — a decent job with a little meaning, a small practice with a little discipline. Everything about you scales further than you have taken it. The harmony you feel is real, but it is a foundation, not a finished building.',
    square: 'Reality keeps auditing your dreams and your dreams keep undermining your reality. You build the sensible life and a fog of meaninglessness seeps in; you chase the meaningful thing and the money, the structure, the ground dissolves. You have oscillated between cynicism and escapism and found both uninhabitable. Here is what this friction is forging, slowly: a faith with load-bearing walls. You are being forced to test every belief against consequence and every structure against the soul, and what survives that double audit — some things are surviving it — cannot be taken from you by anything.',
    sextile: 'You can make meaning practical — design the ritual that actually fits the schedule, the creative practice that survives contact with Monday. When you deliberately connect your spiritual life to your structured life, both improve, and you know this because you have done it in small ways: the walk that became a practice, the discipline that became devotion. The aspect asks you to do it on purpose and at scale, and you keep not asking. Your inner life is better organized than you give it credit for and your outer life more meaningful. Introduce them formally. They are ready to work together.',
    quincunx: 'Your sense of duty and your sense of meaning are permanently misaligned. The responsible path feels spiritually vacant; the meaningful path feels irresponsible; and whichever one you walk, the other sends complaints through your body — the Sunday dread, the guilty daydreams. You keep waiting to find the calling that unifies them. Stop waiting; for you the unification is not on the menu. The adjustment is oscillation with honest bookkeeping: seasons of structure that fund seasons of meaning, each one chosen consciously and time-boxed. The people who look integrated are mostly just quieter about their own version of this.',
  },
  'Pluto/Saturn': {
    conjunction: 'You carry an old fear that endurance is the price of existing — that safety is never granted, only earned through relentless self-control. So you built yourself like a bunker: unshakable habits, deep reserves, a conviction that no one is coming to save you. People sense your gravity and either respect it or step around it; few realize the discipline was forged in something that felt, early on, like survival. Your capacity to endure the unendurable is real and it is your prison\'s key AND its lock. You no longer need to suffer to feel legitimate. Read that again.',
    opposition: 'Authority feels like a threat to you at a depth you rarely admit. Bosses, institutions, systems — you comply on the surface while running a private resistance underneath, and periodically the standoff erupts: the audit, the power struggle, the slow war with someone who controls something you need. You keep meeting immovable objects because you keep projecting your own iron will onto structures and then testing yourself against them. The projection ends when you become your own authority in earnest — not rebellion, but full self-governance. Immovable objects lose interest in people who have stopped pushing on them.',
    trine: 'You wield endurance the way others wield charm. Pressure that breaks people around you barely registers; you can hold a discipline for years, absorb institutional weight, outlast bad regimes at work and at home. Power tends to consolidate around you simply because you are still standing when everyone else has cycled out. The coasting danger is grim: sheer durability can become a substitute for actual choice. You can endure almost anything — including situations you should have left a decade ago. Ask the question you avoid: is this strength in service of something, or just strength with nowhere to go?',
    square: 'Life keeps demolishing what you carefully built, and you keep rebuilding — heavier, stronger, more defended. The job that vanished, the structure that collapsed, the authority that betrayed you: each one taught you to trust systems less and your own grip more, until control itself became the addiction. You feel the clench in your body right now. The forging inside this brutality: you are learning, demolition by demolition, which structures were actually worth building — and the answer keeps shrinking toward the few things that cannot be repossessed. Character. Craft. The people you did not control. Build there.',
    sextile: 'You have a talent for controlled demolition — dismantling what no longer works, methodically, without burning the neighborhood down. The failing process, the dead tradition, the toxic arrangement: you can take these apart with a patience that makes the destruction survivable. When you have used this, it worked. Mostly you do not use it; you maintain instead, servicing structures you know are condemned because starting the demolition feels enormous. It is not enormous — it is sequential, and sequencing is your exact gift. The thing you have been maintaining past its death: begin taking it down this quarter. One bolt at a time.',
    quincunx: 'Your discipline and your depth never work the same shift. You maintain perfect order on the surface while something underneath quietly reorganizes itself — then the underground shift completes and your entire structure suddenly does not fit, and everyone is shocked when steady, reliable you dismantles a whole life. You are not volatile; your transformations are just invisible until they are total. This rhythm is permanent. The adjustment is honest inventory: on a schedule, ask what has already died that you are still maintaining. You always know the answer. You have usually known for about two years.',
  },
  'Neptune/Uranus': {
    conjunction: 'Your visions arrive electrically — not as slow intuitions but as sudden downloads that reorganize everything, leaving you certain of things you cannot yet explain. You live slightly ahead of the available evidence, drawn to whatever is emerging: the new science, the new spirituality, the thing that does not have a name yet. The cost is that the present tense bores you and ordinary consensus reality feels like a hotel you are just staying in. Ground the downloads or lose them — the insight that is not written down, built, or told to someone within a week evaporates completely.',
    opposition: 'You bounce between awakening and disillusionment like they are the only two stations. Something electrifies you — the movement, the practice, the radical idea — then the fog rolls in and it all seems naive, so you defect to skepticism until skepticism itself goes numb. Meanwhile you attract both zealots and cynics, each recruiting you against the other, because you broadcast the war. Both signals are yours: the hunger to be shocked awake and the hunger to dissolve. They are not opposites; disillusionment is just awakening\'s paperwork. Stop switching sides and let each one finish its sentence.',
    trine: 'Your intuition updates itself — while other people\'s inner lives calcify around whatever they believed at twenty-five, yours keeps molting, absorbing new frameworks without crisis. Change of worldview costs you almost nothing, and you quietly pity people who need certainty. The coasting trap: frictionless evolution can mean nothing ever cuts deep enough to scar, and scars are where conviction comes from. You have held every belief lightly and therefore fought for none of them. Somewhere in your open-mindedness is one thing you actually know is true. Defending it out loud would change your life.',
    square: 'Your breakthroughs and your dissolutions keep interrupting each other. Clarity strikes and then fogs over before you can act; surrender begins and then a jolt of restlessness yanks you out of it. Your spiritual life proceeds in static bursts — sudden insight, sudden doubt, sudden reinvention — and you envy people whose inner lives seem to have weather instead of lightning. The friction is forging discernment: you are learning, strike by strike, to tell revelation from static, real dissolution from escapism. Nobody with smooth inner weather ever learns that skill. It only calibrates in a storm.',
    sextile: 'You can catch the emerging thing early — sense where the culture, the field, the conversation is going before it announces itself — and your track record of early calls is quietly excellent. You just rarely act on the catch. You noticed the shift, told no one, invested nothing, and watched it arrive on schedule two years later. This aspect pays out only on placed bets. The next time you feel that specific tingle — the this-is-about-to-matter signal you know exactly how to recognize — put something real behind it: money, hours, your name. Noticing was never the gift. Moving early is.',
    quincunx: 'Your need for transcendence and your need for disruption keep spoiling each other\'s plans. The peace you finally find gets boring and you detonate it; the excitement you chase leaves you spiritually seasick and craving stillness. Meditation feels like sedation, stimulation feels like static, and you have concluded you are bad at both. You are not — they are simply misaligned in you, permanently. The adjustment is alternation with consent: seasons of depth, seasons of voltage, each entered knowingly and exited without shame. What you must stop doing is calling each pole a failure while standing in the other one.',
  },
  'Pluto/Uranus': {
    conjunction: 'You do not renovate — you raze. When change comes through you it is total: identities, careers, relationships ended in a single stroke, the old self left like a shed skin with no forwarding address. People from your previous chapters describe someone who no longer exists, and you feel almost nothing hearing it. This capacity for absolute reinvention is real power, and it doubles as your favorite escape hatch: obliteration is easier than repair, and you know it. The mastery is learning which structures deserve the fire — because some of what you have burned was load-bearing, and you knew that too.',
    opposition: 'Upheaval keeps arriving through other people. The partner who suddenly leaves, the colleague whose crisis detonates your plans, the friend whose transformation reorders your world — you experience yourself as the stable one in a cast of live grenades. Count the grenades. At some point the common denominator becomes the interesting fact. You are drawn to volatile, transforming people because they perform the revolution you refuse to conduct in your own name; their explosions give you change with deniability. Claim one radical act as openly, boringly yours — announced in advance, executed on schedule — and watch the grenades stop finding you.',
    trine: 'Deep change comes to you without catastrophe — you shed selves, habits, and eras smoothly, transforming on a schedule other people would need a crisis to justify. Reinvention is your resting state, and you barely notice you are doing it. The coasting shadow: because transformation is cheap for you, you may never have transformed anything but yourself. All that regenerative voltage, spent privately, on serial self-renovation, while the systems around you — the family pattern, the broken workplace, the community that needs exactly this — stay untouched. Aim it outward once. Changing yourself is your talent. Changing something shared is your assignment.',
    square: 'Change comes for you before you consent to it — the eruption, the exposure, the forced ending that arrives precisely when you had decided to hold still. Your life reads as a series of demolitions you did not schedule, and you have developed a bracing tension, a body that waits for the next quake. Here is what the quakes are forging: you have learned you survive it. Every collapse you were sure would end you turned out to be a wall, not the building. That knowledge — earned, cellular, unfakeable — is the thing this aspect was making the whole time. People can feel it on you.',
    sextile: 'You can spot the crack in any structure — the assumption everyone still obeys but no one believes, the exact place where the old thing will give way. It is a demolition surveyor\'s eye, and it is accurate. What you do with it, mostly, is nothing: you note the crack, predict the collapse privately, and are proven right at no profit. This aspect rewards participation, not prophecy. The next time you see the crack, act on it — be first out of the doomed arrangement, first into the space it vacates, the one who proposes the replacement. Being right early only counts if you move early.',
    quincunx: 'Your revolutions and your transformations run on incompatible clocks. The sudden break you make never reaches deep enough — you change the job, the city, the name, and the underlying pattern commutes right along with you. Meanwhile the deep change that is genuinely underway moves too slowly to satisfy your hunger for rupture, so you interrupt it with another cosmetic explosion. This mismatch is permanent. The adjustment: before any dramatic exit, name the pattern you are actually trying to kill, and check whether leaving touches it at all. Half your escapes were relocations. The pattern has never once failed to find the new address.',
  },
  'Neptune/Pluto': {
    conjunction: 'Your imagination has a basement, and the basement has a door you have learned not to leave open. Your dreams are not decorative — they are chthonic, pulling up material from depths most people\'s fantasies never touch: obsession, death, merger, the dissolve. You are drawn to the hidden layer of everything — the subtext, the occult, the unconscious motive — and people confess things to you they have told no one, sensing you have already been down there. The gift is x-ray vision for the soul. The discipline is coming back up. Always come back up.',
    opposition: 'You keep meeting people who seem to hold the depths for you — the intense ones, the shadowed ones, partners and friends whose darkness or mysticism fascinates you until it engulfs you, and then you surface, swearing off intensity, until the next one. You play the innocent to their underworld, but the underworld is yours; they are just the door you use to visit it deniably. The cycle ends when you take up residence in your own depths — your own shadow work, your own inner descent — and stop needing a guide whose hand you will eventually have to bite to get free.',
    trine: 'You are at ease in psychological deep water that makes other people panic. Grief, endings, the irrational, the taboo — you can sit with all of it, and you become the one others seek out when their lives crack open, because your calm down there is genuine. The coasting risk: comfort with depth is not the same as work in it. You visit the underworld like a local showing tourists around, but you have never dug there for yourself — never taken your own obsessions, wounds, and dreams and transmuted them into something. The ore is yours too. Mine it.',
    square: 'Your dreams and your compulsions keep contaminating each other. What begins as vision curdles into obsession; what begins as surrender turns into being consumed — the escape that became a habit, the fascination that became a possession, the ideal that demanded everything. You have learned, expensively, that your imagination has teeth. This friction is forging the rarest discernment: the ability to tell devotion from addiction, transcendence from self-erasure, the sacred from the merely intense. Each time you name which one is operating — and you are getting faster — you reclaim voltage that used to run you. Eventually you will run it.',
    sextile: 'You can bring buried things gently to the surface — say the unsayable in a way that heals instead of detonates, help people look at what they have been avoiding without shattering them. It is a midwife\'s skill for the unconscious, and when you have used it, people remember the conversation for years. You use it approximately never, because initiating depth feels presumptuous, so you wait for others to open the door you could open kindly yourself. Stop waiting. The friend circling their unspoken thing right now — you know exactly who — needs one precise, gentle question. You already know the question too.',
    quincunx: 'Your longing for dissolution and your instinct for control never stop renegotiating. You crave surrender — to love, to art, to something larger — but the moment surrender approaches, a deep hand on the wheel tightens, and the moment control is secured, the longing starts again. You have called this self-sabotage in both directions. It is neither; it is two survival systems with permanently different agendas, and the adjustment is dosage: chosen containers where you let go completely — the art, the practice, the trusted room — held inside a life you otherwise steer. Total surrender and total control were never options. Alternation, on your terms, is.',
  },
};
